    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-05-28T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-05-28T12:00:00-05:00" n="26"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 491</seg>
                </opener>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.13/5–2851: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom (</hi>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GWS1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gifford</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <hi rend="italic">) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d26fn1">Repeated to Vienna, Paris, Moscow, and Frankfurt for
                            <persName corresp="#p_RSJ1">Reber</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-05-28T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 28, 1951—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6218. Minford of <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> Aust desk, who
                    accompanied <persName corresp="#p_MHS1">Morrison</persName> to Vienna,<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d26fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_MHS1">Herbert Morrison</persName>, British Secretary
                        of State for Foreign Affairs, visited Vienna May 22–23, following a visit to
                        Bonn the previous 3 days.</note> told <gloss target="#t_Emboff1"
                        >EmbOff</gloss> May 28 fol points were covered in Fon-Secy’s conversations
                    with Aust officials: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Ger assets in Aust</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_MHS1"
                                >Morrison</persName> gave strong assurance to <persName
                                corresp="#p_GK2">Gruber</persName> that UK fully intended implement
                            para 11 of Art 35 of draft treaty by which three West powers relinquish
                            to Aust Ger assets in Aust.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Oil undertaking</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_GK2"
                                >Gruber</persName> was at first skittish on this subj; after
                                <persName corresp="#p_MHS1">Morrison</persName> reiterated
                            importance attached by UK to declaration <persName corresp="#p_GK2"
                                >Gruber</persName> agreed that undertaking wld be given.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Occupation costs</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_GK2"
                                >Gruber</persName> emphasized that shld Aust treaty not be soon
                            forthcoming wld be psychologically important that shld appear Aust was
                            passing occ costs only to Russians; any money paid to Fr and Brit wld
                            have to be in nature of voluntary contribution to West def. Minford
                            added that occ costs question may arise again before end of year as 140
                            million schillings will probably not cover Brit costs for 1951 (Vienna’s
                            tel 1813 to Dept Feb 21<note n="3" xml:id="d26fn3">Document
                            479.</note>).</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Requisitioning</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_FDL1"
                                >Figl</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_GK2">Gruber</persName>
                            urged that UK derequisition as many properties as possible and fill
                            housing needs by construction new properties which wld later revert to
                            Aust. <persName corresp="#p_MHS1">Morrison</persName> said <persName
                                corresp="#p_CSHA1">Caccia</persName> wld discuss this problem with
                            Aust officials but did not hold out much hope that funds cld be found
                            for such construction.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Aust assets in UK</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_FDL1"
                                >Figl</persName> said Hartenau of Aust Natl Bank wld proceed to UK
                            to discuss question of disposition of Aust assets in UK totalling about
                            600,000 pounds.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Raw materials</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_FDL1"
                                >Figl</persName> pointed out Aust economy dependent on imports of
                            raw materials and said Aust had no def industries into which workers
                            made idle by shortages cld be channeled. He mentioned conclusion of new
                            agreement to ship timber to UK as indication Aust desire to cooperate
                            and expressed hope that Aust needs wld be taken into consideration in
                            distribution raw materials. In reply <persName corresp="#p_MHS1"
                                >Morrison</persName> outlined difficulties UK itself was having in
                            procuring essential materials and referred to Stoke’s trip to Wash in
                            this regard. <persName corresp="#p_MHS1">Morrison</persName> mentioned
                            that Aust might export raw steel to UK because of tight raw materials
                            situation, <persName corresp="#p_FDL1">Figl</persName> suggested that UK
                            and Aust consider establishment of “quota controls” for their
                            trade.</item>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Coalition govt</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_MHS1"
                                >Morrison</persName> advised reps of both People’s Party and
                            Socialists to continue with coalition govt. According to Minford,
                            neither was very happy with this advice.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0075" n="1041" xml:id="pg_1041"/>
                <p>Minford thought <gloss target="#t_FonSecy1">FonSecy</gloss> had made good
                    impression in Aust, due in no small measure to fact that he was “indefatigable”
                    and apparently enjoyed his visit.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GWS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gifford</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
